How to Create RDS in AWS
Step 1: Go to RDS
  *.Login to AWS Management Console
  *.Search for RDS → Open Amazon RDS dashboard
Step 2: Create Database
1.Click “Create database”
2.Choose Creation method:
  *.Standard create → full customization
  *.Easy create → AWS picks defaults (good for beginners)
Step 3: Choose Engine
MySQL:
  *.PostgreSQL
  *.MariaDB
  *.Oracle
  *.SQL Server
  *.Amazon Aurora
Example: MySQL
Step 4: Database Settings
1.Edition / Version → Choose DB version (e.g., MySQL 8.0)
2.Templates →
*.Dev/Test
*.Production
*.Free Tier (if eligible) 
3.DB instance identifier → Name (e.g., mydb-instance)
4.Credentials → Master username & password
Step 5: Instance Size
*.DB instance class (compute power & RAM)
    *.Example: db.t3.micro (Free tier)
*.Storage
    *.General Purpose SSD (gp3) or Provisioned IOPS
    *.Choose allocated storage (e.g., 20 GB)
Step 6: Connectivity
1.VPC → Select your VPC
2.Subnet group → Choose subnets for DB
3.Public access:
    *.Yes → If you want to connect from outside AWS
    *.No → Only internal apps can access
4.VPC security group → Allow access (e.g., MySQL port 3306)
Step 7: Additional Settings
*.Initial database name (optional)
*.Backup retention (default 7 days)
*.Enable auto backups (recommended for production)
*.Enable monitoring (optional)
Step 9: Connect to RDS
  *.Go to Databases → Select your DB
  *.Copy the Endpoint (DNS name)
  *.Connect using client:
For MySQL:
        mysql -h <RDS-endpoint> -u <username> -p
Example:
        mysql -h mydb-instance.c9akciq3df2.us-east-1.rds.amazonaws.com -u admin -p
                             (Now you have a running RDS database)
